@dmed256 you suggested in https://github.com/CartoDB/cartoframes/issues/85 a method for returning dataframes from longer running queries. Here we could have a flag or another method for returning the lnglat'd version of the table/dataframe. I envision us adding more than the lnglat flag for adding geometries.. e.g., street-level geocoding, routing, etc. 

But here, we could have a simple new method (or flag to status), which indicates that when `status=done`, do `cc.read('tablename')` to return the carto'd dataframe.

What do you think? Too soon?

@readroberts the path to "libautohintlib.a" referenced here is only temporary and specific to @schriftgestalt Xcode setup at the time he edited the xcodeproj. 
Could that be the reason why I cannot successfully run "BuildAll.sh" fo autohint?
This is clang's error:

    ld: library not found for -lautohintlib  

The only way I can build autohint on OS X is by doing this:
- build `libautohintlib.a` using its own Xcode project `autohintlib.xcodeproj`;
- copy the resulting `autohint/autohintlib/exe/osx/debug/libautohintlib.a` to both `autohint/exe/osx/debug` and to `autohint/exe/osx/release`;
- finally, run autohint's BuildAll.sh script

I considered that, but it has the problematic side effect that multiple calls to write labels would not do the right thing:

```python
bucket.labels  # {'foo': ..., 'bar': ..., 'baz': ...}
bucket.labels = {'bar': ..., 'baz': ..., 'bacon': ...}
bucket._label_removals  # {'foo'}
bucket.labels = {'baz': ..., 'bacon': ...}
bucket._label_removals  # {'bar'}; should be {'foo', 'bar'}
```

Good question. I thought about that and the settled with this idea:
I think generally it is a good practice especially when the call stack is relatively simple. However in cases where the same args get passed further down into other functions, things may look confusing, so making it non-optional would make it clear during debugging where the args are came from, and also more clear for readers that just want to skim the code.

For example:
```
def resolve(..., sources=false, javadoc=false)
  x(sources, javadoc)

def x(sources,javadoc)
  y(sources,javadoc)

def y(sources, javadoc):
  // do other things
```

basically as a reader, it is hard to tell if `sources`, `javadoc` in `y` actually comes from the default value in `resolve` or the caller of `resolve` unless going back on the stack and then check how `resolve` is getting called, whereas non-optional args would make it clear that `sources`, `javadoc` in `y` is the exactly how `resolve` is getting called.

Minor note, but I've sometimes found it inconvenient to encode data in the keys of json objects.

Sometimes the slightly more verbose version is more helpful because the keys are static and self-describing, e.g.:

```json
{
  "kinds": [
    {
      "name": "video",
      "extensions": ["mp4", "ogg", "wmv"]
    },
    {
      "name": "audio",
      "extensions": ["mp3", "wav"]
    }
  ]
}
```

- I think it would be clearer if we renamed `payload` to `claims_as dict` and `claims` to `claims_as_string`
- The payload should be the simplest it can be to demonstrate the functionality being tested. Currently there are three string fields and two number fields. We should change this to remove the duplicated ones and test more types, something like:
```
claims_as_dict = {
  'data': [
    {
      'string': 'something',
      'boolean': true,
      'number': 10,
      'decimal': 10.1
      'null': null
    }
  ]
}
```

@galgalesh @johnsca Just because you can, doesn't mean you should :smile: Any channel can be used as a pseudo-(async)-rpc mechanism, provided both ends agree on the protocol.  I was debating about whether complex interactions _between_ charms should be encouraged or not.  Already people ask about "how do I transfer my state flag to the other charm", which reinforces the notion that juju & charms are a kind of distributed programming model (which of course, it _can_ be).

@galgalesh I think you're in favour of increased complexity so that more complex behaviours can be offered _by default_ from charms.reactive? I'm actually in favour of _simpler_ behaviour in charms.reactive, and building out more complex behaviour in a layer (or other library) _if_ that's the route some authors which to go.  I'm _worried_ about having default complex behaviour as it may put off people trying out Juju as an alternative to other configuration management tools.

@johnsca I don't disagree that relations can be used for more complex behaviour.  I would argue that reasoning about that behaviour becomes exponentially more difficult if the data on a relation becomes more dynamic (other than simply changing state due to configuration changes rippling through a set of charms, or leadership changes, etc.).  Otherwise charms become more like 'services' rather than managing services?

@johnsca I also tend to agree on the interfaces; they are effectively 'schema-in-code' in that they enforce the format of the data shared on the boundary between two charms, and also how a charm can access it.  It's an non-versioned schema, but that's an argument for another day. 

My contribution to this debate, possibly defunct, is about how complex it is to write a charm to do the basic job of installing, configuring and managing the lifetime of pieces of software that need to be configured to talk to each other.  More complex behaviours _can_ be built on top of the basic facilities that Juju provides; should this be by default, or as an additional library?

Additionally, we have the pattern `make*` for factories in other places here. I think that that is a little confusing. The Immutable pattern seems to be `RecordFactory`, so  think `*Factory` makes sense? Then, we end up using just like `Map`:

```
const map = Map();
const record = CommunicationKernelspecsFactory();
```

Ya?

if NamedTemporaryFile throws as exception, then temp_filename will not be defined.  one possible strategy is:

```
if 'temp_filename' in locals() and os.path.isfile(temp_filename):
```

another strategy is to define temp_filename before the loop.
